<gco:CharacterString>This Digital Elevation Model (DEM) of the bedrock surface elevation in Iowa was compiled using all available data, principally information from GEOSAM, supplemented with well and boring information from the Iowa DOT, exposure reports from Iowa Geological & Water Survey reports and files, and the Department of Soil Conservation county soil maps for Iowa. The soil maps were especially valuable, since they identified soils that encountered bedrock within the soil horizon, and less dependably also spot-located rock exposures. A 50 foot contour interval was chosen for the map because it was considered to best represent the accuracy of the well data, allowed for fairly good representation of the bedrock surface in areas with limited well control, and was mappable in high relief areas (the contours packed so close together that it precluded mapping or forced the software to snap-join contours). The 50 foot contour interval also allowed areas where bedrock was present within the soil horizon (2-3 feet) to be treated as areas of exposures. In these areas the bedrock elevation was mapped as only slightly below the surface elevation, so contours on the 7\ufffd\ufffd' topographic maps were closely followed in mapping the bedrock elevation. Consequently, on the completed map of bedrock elevation, these areas display much more contorted and crenulated contour lines than the areas where only drill control was utilized.</gco:CharacterString>          </gmd:abstract>          <gmd:purpose>             <gco:CharacterString>This digital, geographically referenced data set was developed by the Iowa Department of Natural Resources to carry out agency responsibilities related to management, protection, and development of Iowa's natural resources.</gco:CharacterString>          </gmd:purpose>          <gmd:credit>             <gco:CharacterString>Recognized for significant contributions to the maps production: Bill J.         </gmd:report>          <gmd:lineage>             <gmd:LI_Lineage>                <gmd:processStep>                   <gmi:LE_ProcessStep>                      <gmd:description>                         <gco:CharacterString>MAPPING OF THE BEDROCK SURFACE ELEVATION: When most of the digital database was assembled, work began on mapping of the elevation of the bedrock surface. All bedrock elevation mapping was done using ArcGis (ERSI) software. Since mapping was at a 50 foot contour interval, the areas of shallow-to-bedrock soils (bedrock less than 24 inches) were considered to be exposures for mapping purposes. Georeferenced U.S.G.S. 7-1/2 minute topographic quadrangle maps of the area being mapped were loaded into the ArcGis project and white background and green forested areas on the maps were rendered transparent. When mapping in the areas of the shallow-to-bedrock polygons, the bedrock elevation contours were drawn directly on surface contour lines of the 7-1/2 minute quadrangle maps through these polygons and then continued into areas of higher surface elevation between closely-spaced polygons. In areas with no shallow-to-bedrock polygons GEOSAM well data was utilized to control location of the bedrock elevation contours. Proximity of shallow to bedrock soil polygons to the area being mapped were also used as an indicator of bedrock depth. Even if the polygon did not intersect a 50-foot contour being mapped, it still provided a close estimate of bedrock depth in its area. Using these data to control location of contour lines the elevation of the bedrock surface was contoured by an IGWS staff geologist. The lines were drawn to be consistent with observed patterns and characteristics of stream incision into geologic materials at the land surface. Where possible, contours were joined at map edges to current bedrock elevation maps from adjoining areas or states. In areas of limited control contours were spaced at equal distances from one another based upon bedrock elevations of available well points. In areas of high control density, such as areas of shallow-to bedrock soils, the contours are very crenulated and complex, whereas in areas of only sparse well control the contours are more smooth and flowing. This allows the map user to tell at a glance how much control was present in any given area and therefore the accuracy of the map's representation of the true bedrock surface elevation in that area. In other words, areas of complex contours imply areas of higher map reliability than areas of smooth flowing contours.</gco:CharacterString>                      </gmd:description> <gco:CharacterString>CONVERSION OF THE BEDROCK CONTOUR LINES TO A GRID: (1) Attempts to convert the contour lines to a gird were not very satisfying because of the number of vertices on many of the contour lines, and only a tin could be generated which resulted in a very stepped surface of relief. Therefore, a third party product, ET Geo Wizards conversion of polyline to points (vertices selected) was utilized to generate a point file of all vertices of all the contour lines. This created a point shapefile of over 4,000,000 points of elevation. (2) Then using the TopoToRaster tool from ArcGis 3D Analyst Tools this point file was selected as the Feature Layer, Elevation as the Field, and Point Elevation as the Type. Additionally the state border of Iowa was added as a Feature Layer and Boundary was selected as the Type. A 110 meter Output cell size was selected for generation of the grid. All other defaults were left alone. (3) The resultant grid was then generated from this approach.</gco:CharacterString>                      </gmd:description>                      <gmd:dateTime>
